<tr><td>&#160;y&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.26&#160;</td>        <td>&#160;w&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.52&#160;</td></tr>
<tr><td>&#160;c&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.24&#160;</td>        <td>&#160;f&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.13&#160;</td></tr>
<tr><td>&#160;f&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.17&#160;</td>        <td>&#160;g&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.13&#160;</td></tr>
<tr><td>&#160;g&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.10&#160;</td>        <td>&#160;y&#160;</td><td align='right'>2.04&#160;</td></tr>
<tr><td>&#160;p&#160;</td><td align='right'>1.70&#160;</td>        <td>&#160;p&#160;</td><td align='right'>1.74&#160;</td></tr>
<tr><td>&#160;b&#160;</td><td align='right'>1.52&#160;</td>        <td>&#160;b&#160;</td><td align='right'>1.64&#160;</td></tr>
</table></p>

<p>The most significant difference I can see is the i: 7.24% for Dickens and 6.41% for Thackeray.
And Thackeray's s, h, and r are more common than Dickens'.
But Thackeray used more e's and fewer t's.  It's all a wash as far as I can see.
Maybe there's a slight truth to it, but enough to make a difference to a type designer? I don't see it.
</p>

